Ethics Review Feedback (L1) (ORE # 21001)

ORE Ethics Application System
Dear Researcher: This note is to advise you that the ethics review of your OR...
3:55 PM (19 hours ago)
Dear Researcher: This note is to advise you that the ethics review of your OR...

ORE Ethics Application System

3:55 PM (19 hours ago)
to edith.law, wrcallag, josh.bradshaw, trttse
Dear Researcher:

This note is to advise you that the ethics review of your ORE application:

Title: A framework for hybrid machine and human computation for the accurate and scalable analysis of human clinical EEG recordings
ORE #: 21001
Principal/Co-Investigator: Edith Law (edith.law@uwaterloo.ca)
Student Investigator: William Callaghan (wrcallag@uwaterloo.ca)
Student Investigator: Josh Bradshaw (josh.bradshaw@uwaterloo.ca)
Student Investigator: Timmy Rong Tian Tse (trttse@uwaterloo.ca)

has been completed.   Acceptance of the application on ethical grounds is conditional on revisions and/or additional information.  Below is a summary of recommendations for revisions as well as any related comments or questions.


-----------------------------------------------
A. Comments on the Recruitment Process:

i. Recruitment email for study 0

a. Replaced "compensation" with "remuneration".

b. Outline how to sign up for the study (i.e., do people email Edith?)

c. Remove the last sentence in the last paragraph with Maureen's name and contact information. This is not needed in a recruitment email.

d. It is assumed you need to obtain ethics clearance by the Sunnybrook/UHN REB since the study will take place on site at the hospital. Please clarify and add the relevant statements.

-----------------------------------------------
B. Comments on the Information Letter and/or Consent Form:

i. Information letter for study 0

a. Remove the reference to "HIT" as this is not applicable.

b. Add the taxable statement (see https://uwaterloo.ca/research/office-research-ethics/research-human-participants/application-process/samples-and-other-supporting-materials#remuneration)

c. More explanation is needed to explain what it is participants are being asked to do for the study. What you have is too vague. Also, an explanation to explain the video-record is needed (why you are doing it, how it will be used, etc.)

d. Add "without loss of remuneration" after "ceasing to answer questions".

d. Outline the time commitment.

e. A signed consent form is needed to outline an agreement to participate. Combine the video consent form with a participation consent form.

f. Refer to the samples at https://uwaterloo.ca/research/office-research-ethics/research-human-participants/application-process/samples-and-other-supporting-materials/information-consent-samples#interviews (have a look at the interview samples and the multiple consent form at the bottom of the page)

ii. Information letter for study 1

a. See comment below re: pay for performance.

b. More explanation is needed to explain what it is participants are being asked to do for the study. What you have is too vague. Also, an explanation to explain the video-record is needed (why you are doing it, how it will be used, etc.)

c. Outline the time commitment.

d. Explain how remuneration is provided if they decide to withdraw. See the crowdsourcing guidelines noted below.

e. Remove "and those will be anonymized". The information/data is anonymous since you do not know who participated.

f. Refer to the web-survey samples (see the url above) and revise the consent form for online studies.

g. Add the PATRIOT act statements as needed. See the web-survey sample noted above.

-----------------------------------------------
C. Comments on the Survey or Interview Protocol:

No comments.

-----------------------------------------------
D. Comments on the Procedures and Methodology:

i. 101 application form

a. Section C2b - The uWaterloo crowdsourcing guidelines preclude researchers from not allowing person to take part in a study because an approval rating has been assigned to them by a third party. See https://uwaterloo.ca/research/sites/ca.research/files/uploads/files/crowdsourcing_guidelines_access_check_done.pdf  Please confirm this will not be done.

b. Section C4 - Remuneration may only be based on performance are when researchers clearly indicate what the standards are for payment and non-payment are and still allow individuals to withdraw from the study. The information and consent letter can be edited to clearly indicate that there are specific performance demands required in order to receive payment. People still have to be able to withdraw, and people still have to have the ability to skip any question that they do not feel comfortable responding to.   You need to be clear what sort of response would cause non-payment and what participants should do if they want to withdraw or skip a question.  IN essence, if you're paying for performance, you have to let people know what the rules for acceptable performance are.  From our perspective, it would be acceptable for you to set some reasonable benchmarks for ascertaining what 'junk' data or participation would look like but these need to be very clearly outlined to part!
 icipants. People may, for example, enter a string of nonsense characters in order to move through an online study--not necessarily  because they are hoping to 'cheat'--but because they do not wish to answer a particular question. So if this is a reason that individuals may not be paid, then you have to clearly indicate that, and what to do if they do not wish to answer a question (e.g. -leave a field blank or enter n/a). If non-payment is predicated on something specific (like entering random characters into a survey field instead of responding or skipping a question, or (spending too little time on completion of the survey), then that has to be very clearly explained in the IC (e.g., 'Note that compensation is based on performance; while you may decline to answer any questions that you prefer not to answer by leaving them blank or withdraw  from this survey at any time by clicking on the 'Exit this survey' link located on each page of the survey, compensation will not be a!
 warded if responses are not meaningful (e.g. random words, letter strings), or if participants do not meet  the study eligibility criteria.)

ii. What online data collection system are you using? Is it a system you have created yourself or is it a US or Canadian system?


-----------------------------------------------
E. Comments on the Feedback Letter/Letter of Appreciation:

No comments.

-----------------------------------------------
F. Other Comments:

i. 101 application form

a. Section A1 - Add Andrew and Jigme as co-investigators.

b. Section A7 - Why has Harvard and McGill be included here?

c. Section A8 - Why are some of the approvals more than 1 years ago? Also, why is an approval from McGill or Harvard not listed since they are mention in A7?

d. Section C1a - Add secondary use of information here as well.

ii. Why was a modification request form provided from UOttawa for the Bhutan study. It is assumed the proposed study with the Bhutan Epilepsy project will be submitted as new 101 application. Is the correct?

**************

Researcher(s), this summarizes the feedback from the ethics review of your application.  Revised materials should be provided within ten days to the Office of Research Ethics in hard copy or by email to ohrac@uwaterloo.ca   <mailto:ohrac@uwaterloo.ca>

Please indicate the ORE number to which the changes refer when submitting revisions and highlight or use track changes in the revised section(s) to expedite the ethics review of these documents.

Please note that if revisions and responses to comments are not received by the ORE within 9 months of receiving this email and the paper copy of the feedback the file will be closed.  Prior to closing the file the principal investigator will receive two email messages concerning the non-response to this ethics review email.

The corresponding study may not be started, including recruitment of participants, until the full ethics review certificate has been issued.

Please feel free to contact me at the extension given below about any of the above comments.

Best wishes,

----------------------------------
Julie Joza, MPH
Senior Manager
Office of Research Ethics
NH 1027
519.888.4567 ext. 38535
jajoza@uwaterloo.ca

Hello! Thank you for the feedback. Its not 100% clear to me how the revision...

Edith Law

4:43 PM (18 hours ago)
to ORE, Julie, Josh
Hi Julie,

Some questions:

Section A.i.d.  Do we need ethics clearance from hospitals simply because we are bringing our study to the hospital site?  If so, suppose that we ask technicians to participate on our study outside of the hospital (e.g., in a room at the public library), using equipments and data that is unrelated to the hospital, would we still need approval from Sunnybrook?

Section F.  We included a lot of extra materials with the ORE application because our grant is a multi-institutional grant between Sunnybrook, McGill and Waterloo.  However, the human subject studies that we describe in the ORE is performed solely by the PI and students at University of Waterloo.  In this case, can we remove the dependencies, if any, on other institutions?


Edith.

> e. Remove "and those will be anonymized". The information/data is anonymous since you do not know who participated.
>
> f. Refer to the web-survey samples (see the url above) and revise the consent form for online studies.
>
> g. Add the PATRIOT act statements as needed. See the web-survey sample noted above.

>
> No comments.

> D. Comments on the Procedures and Methodology:
>
> i. 101 application form
>
> a. Section C2b - The uWaterloo crowdsourcing guidelines preclude researchers from not allowing person to take part in a study because an approval rating has been assigned to them by a third party. See https://uwaterloo.ca/research/sites/ca.research/files/uploads/files/crowdsourcing_guidelines_access_check_done.pdf  Please confirm this will not be done.
>
> b. Section C4 - Remuneration may only be based on performance are when researchers clearly indicate what the standards are for payment and non-payment are and still allow individuals to withdraw from the study. The information and consent letter can be edited to clearly indicate that there are specific performance demands required in order to receive payment. People still have to be able to withdraw, and people still have to have the ability to skip any question that they do not feel comfortable responding to.   You need to be clear what sort of response would cause non-payment and what participants should do if they want to withdraw or skip a question.  IN essence, if you're paying for performance, you have to let people know what the rules for acceptable performance are.  From our perspective, it would be acceptable for you to set some reasonable benchmarks for ascertaining what 'junk' data or participation would look like but these need to be very clearly outlined to part!
> icipants. People may, for example, enter a string of nonsense characters in order to move through an online study--not necessarily  because they are hoping to 'cheat'--but because they do not wish to answer a particular question. So if this is a reason that individuals may not be paid, then you have to clearly indicate that, and what to do if they do not wish to answer a question (e.g. -leave a field blank or enter n/a). If non-payment is predicated on something specific (like entering random characters into a survey field instead of responding or skipping a question, or (spending too little time on completion of the survey), then that has to be very clearly explained in the IC (e.g., 'Note that compensation is based on performance; while you may decline to answer any questions that you prefer not to answer by leaving them blank or withdraw  from this survey at any time by clicking on the 'Exit this survey' link located on each page of the survey, compensation will not be a!
> warded if responses are not meaningful (e.g. random words, letter strings), or if participants do not meet  the study eligibility criteria.)
>
> ii. What online data collection system are you using? Is it a system you have created yourself or is it a US or Canadian system?
>
